{
  "answer": "In Mirza Ghalib's ghazal \"Aah ko chahiye ik umr asar hote tak,\" the following couplet exemplifies the polysemy of *shab* (night) fused with *furqat* (separation), evoking both the literal night of a lover's parting and the Sufi *shab-e-furqat*—an eternal, mystical night of separation from the Divine Beloved:\n\n> Ta-qayamat **shab-e-furqat** mein guzar jaayegi umr  \n> Saat din hum pe bhi bhaari hain seher hote tak  \n> \n> This separation lasts till judgment's dawn;  \n> For me, a week is heavy, till the morning's light.[^1]\n\nThe spiritual reading is unambiguously activated by *ta-qayamat* (\"until Doomsday\" or \"judgment's dawn\"), stretching the lover's anguish into cosmic, eschatological time—a hallmark of Sufi imagery where earthly *furqat* mirrors the soul's primordial exile from God, awaiting resurrection's union.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/03-aah-ko-chahiye-ik-umr-asar-hote-tak/translation/#p-1ec337).\n\n[^2]: Ibid., chapter overview context from transliteration variant read_chapter.",
